@NODE GFA " GFA's problem!"

GFA-Basic has a problem that chews up 40 bytes for each program that is run.
This can quickly zap system memory on busy machines. I asked John if he could
find the problem, and fortunately he was able to trace the problem.

From John's fingers:

       Well  I have found your memory loss.  In the INIT code for GFA it
       is  opening a port.  This port is opening in the INIT code but is
       never  closed  anywhere.   Thus everytime it is run a new message
       port is created thus lossing memory each time.  I am not sure how
       to fix it.  I could fix each program very easily by just removing
       the  instructions  and  this  would  fix  each  program but every
       program would need changing each time.

       If  you  are confident enough your self and want to try.  Using a
       binary file editor look for the sequence of bytes

       61 00 xx xx  change to  4E 71 4E 71
       2D 40 14 1A  change to  4E 71 4E 71
       61 00 xx xx
       3D 7C 2E 2C

       xx means these bytes change depending on the program

       Changing these to the specified numbers will change the

       bsr.w 	CreatePort
       move.l	d0,(Offset,a6)

       into 

       NOP
       NOP
       NOP
       NOP

       Meaning that the port will no be created an thus does not need to
       be freed

All the M-Tag package programs have been suitably adjusted after compiling
each executable. Those running other GFA programs may like to manually edit
the fields above to fix the problem.

How do you know if you have a GFA program? Easy! Simply load the executable
into a text reader and go to the bottom of the file. You will see
'GFA-BASIC-Screen' if it is a GFA program.

@ENDNODE
